      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The West continues to delay financial support to upgrade nuclear power plants in the former Soviet Union and Eastern Europe (editorial, May 14). The answer, however, is not to build more coal-burning plants. Yes, nuclear accidents do not respect national borders, but neither does pollution from coal. Trading potential environmental hazards from nuclear plants for certain damage from the  mining, transportation and burning of coal would do more harm than good.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The West continues to delay financial support to upgrade nuclear power plants in the former Soviet Union and Eastern Europe (editorial, May 14). The answer, however, is not to build more coal-burning plants. Yes, nuclear accidents do not respect national borders, but neither does pollution from coal. Trading potential environmental hazards from nuclear plants for certain damage from the  mining, transportation and burning of coal would do more harm than good.</p>
        <p>Many nuclear reactor units in Eastern Europe can be made acceptably safe, as they have been in the Czech Republic. We should help these countries meet Western standards.</p>
        <p>GEOFFREY ROTHWELL  Stanford, Calif., May 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
